04510nmm a2200661Ia 9780520912496DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t19931993cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209124967 a10.1525/97805209124962doi  a(DE-B1597)649409  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aJK6141b.B37 1992eb 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a353.9776/012201 aBarzelay/Altshuler, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBreaking Through Bureaucracy :bA New Vision for Managing in Government /cBarzelay/Altshuler; ed. by Babak J. Armajani, Michael Barzelay, Alan Altshuler. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1993] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (237 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book attacks the conventional wisdom that bureaucrats are bunglers and the system can't be changed. Michael Barzelay and Babak Armajani trace the source of much poor performance in government to the persistent influence of what they call the bureaucratic paradigm—a theory built on such notions as central control, economy and efficiency, and rigid adherence to rules. Rarely questioned, the bureaucratic paradigm leads competent and faithful public servants—as well as politicians—unwittingly to impair government's ability to serve citizens by weakening, misplacing, and misdirecting accountability.How can this system be changed? Drawing on research sponsored by the Ford Foundation/Harvard University program on Innovations in State and Local Government, this book tells the story of how public officials in one state, Minnesota, cast off the conceptual blinders of the bureaucratic paradigm and experimented with ideas such as customer service, empowering front-line employees to resolve problems, and selectively introducing market forces within government. The author highlights the arguments government executives made for the changes they proposed, traces the way these changes were implemented, and summarizes the impressive results. This approach provides would-be bureaucracy busters with a powerful method for dramatically improving the way government manages the public's business.Generalizing from the Minnesota experience and from similar efforts nationwide, the book proposes a new paradigm that will reframe the perennial debate on public management. With its carefully analyzed ideas, real-life examples, and closely reasoned practical advice, Breaking Through Bureaucracy is indispensable to public managers and students of public policy and administration.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAdministrative agenciesxManagementxMinnesota. 0aAdministrative agencieszMinnesotaxManagement. 0aBureaucracyxMinnesota. 0aBureaucracyxUnited States. 0aBureaucracyzMinnesota. 0aBureaucracyzUnited States. 0aExecutive departmentsxManagementxMinnesota. 0aExecutive departmentszMinnesotaxManagement. 0aOrganizational changexMinnesota. 0aOrganizational changezMinnesota. 0aPublic administration. 4aGeneral. 4aPolitical Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAltshuler, Alan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aArmajani, Babak J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBarzelay, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt0 cprintz978052007801740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091249640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520912496423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520912496/original  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles